st of Data objects into a single large Data object.\n        data, slices \u003d self.collate(data_list)\n        \n        # Save everything to the processed file.\n        torch.save((data, slices, mean, std), self.processed_paths[0])\n        print(f\"✅ Saved QA dataset with normalized targets to \u0027{self.processed_paths[0]}\u0027\")\n\n# --- Main Execution Block ---\n# This allows the script to be run directly from the command line.\nif __name__ \u003d\u003d \"__main__\":\n    print(\"--- Starting QA-QM9 Dataset Conversion ---\")\n    # This will trigger the download() and process() methods if the file doesn\u0027t exist.\n    # It will create the \u0027./processed/\u0027 directory automatically.\n    dataset \u003d QAQM9Dataset(root\u003d\u0027.\u0027)\n    print(f\"✅ Successfully created and loaded {len(dataset)} QA molecules.\")\n    print(\"📊 Sample molecule data:\")\n    print(dataset[0])\n```\n\n### Instructions\n\n1.  **Save the Code:** In your home directory (`/home/player1/`), save the code above into a new file named `qa_qm9_converter.py`.\n\n2.  **Run the Converter:** From your terminal (with the `toroidal_sim_env` activated), run the script:\n    ```bash\n    python qa_qm9_converter.py\n    ```\n\n3.  **What to Expect:**\n    *   You will see PyTorch Geometric download the raw QM9 dataset (this might take a few minutes).\n    *   Then, you will see a `tqdm` progress bar as it processes the 10,000 molecules.\n    *   Finally, it will print a success message.\n\n4.  **Verify the File:** After it finishes, you can check that the file was created successfully:\n    ```bash\n    ls processed/\n    ```\n    You should see `data_qaqm9.pt` listed.\n\n5.  **Run the Regressor:** Now that the data exists, you can run the main script again without error:\n    ```bash\n    python regressor.py\n    ```",
